<br>
Secondly, for the people who have stood up and said they have witnessed the injustices that happen within guilds, at great risk of stepping on toes, props to you.  I know that many people fear not getting in a good guild.  I think by this time you realize that if a guild doesn't want to treat you as an individual then it really doesn't matter anyway if they invite you, you're better off without them.<br>
<br>
Many people in game have asked me why I am not guilded.  When Jules posted his question I thought this would be a good time to outline why I remain unguilded.  While my choices may seem negative I have a solid reason behind them.  I don't look for a guild to do things for me, I look for a guild to do things with.  Its not a subtle difference.  <br>
<br>
Many people in this thread have accused me of being bitter.  I was in Promethian Order from Level 28 to 55.  I guess you could say I was one of the few remaining old timers.  PO has seen some very rough times. I stuck with PO, even when it seemed that PO was about to disband, and I think I was pretty essential in their regrowth.  I have seen internal fighting, an attempted coup d'tat and many other things that would have torn a lesser guild apart.<br>
<br>
Regardless of what anyone may think, I still think PO is a good guild.  Keadaian, while he has his faults, works very hard to provide a common source of fun for many members.  I disagreed with guild priorities, loot distribution, communication of guild objectives and guild growth but it never became a bitter issue.  I like to think that I still have friends in PO. <br>
<br>
As a matter of fact, I still run into people in game who are amazed that I left PO because I was so discreet about it.  I left without fanfare or a big fuss.  No big post on a public board for the whole world to see.  Does that sound like a bitter guildie? <br>
<br>
Like I said earlier, I am not going to say what I want a guild to do for me because then I would be a user.   <p>Herder
