 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ukeadaiansongborne.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Keadaian Songborne</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Contributing Member</span><br>  Posts: 207<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/10/01 11:11:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=345.topic&index=71>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: to all unguilded level 46plus here...</span><hr size=1> Going WAY off topic here for a moment but what the hell... <br>
<br>
Communism works well in any smalled closed community that accepts it.  There are plenty of examples of real life communism at work, the most oft quoted being the Kibbutzes in Israel.  Guilds are a fairly good structure for communism as well.<br>
<br>
Herder left w/ a minimum of fanfare because he was clear as to what his difference of opinion was with me and a good portion of the rest of the guild.  It was a seperation that took some time to become clear, but we really were going in a different direction than he wanted to and over the course of a few weeks and many discussion in /gu it was clear to him and us that it was best for him.  As a result of his honesty and the open discussions, there was never any feeling of betrayal -- nobody had any reason whatsoever to doubt his reasons for leaving.  I have a lot of respect for him for being so forthcoming about it.<br>
<br>
I think there are a lot of people that read this that agree with much of what Herder had to say.  However, the way he phrased it, laced with Orwellian undertones, will keep many people from coming out in support of his poiints.<br>
<br>
Hell, I agree with some of what Herder had to say.<br>
<br>
I don't honestly think there is such a thing as a perfect method of dristributing high end loot.  I think there are good ways and bad ways, and even the good ways have flaws.  In PO loot is assigned by class leaders, division leaders or me, depending on the loot.  Most of the time there's a fair amount of discussion between the officers before it's awarded.  Sometimes we make mistakes.  I can think of several such instances.  In my heart of hearts however I think most members of PO know that the officers truly try to do what is best for the guild as a whole.<br>
<br>
VI has chosen to make the high end game a situation in which you need multiple groups to face down a single mob.  By far the most effective strategy is to have a small number of warriors that take turns focusing the mobs aggro onto them.  It is far more mana efficient and workable to have all of the clerics keeping one tank standing then to have the mob rampaging from player to player.  Given that, if a guild wants to kill bigger and bigger mobs, it's critical that they have a small number of tanks that have as much AC as possible so they can stand toe to toe with the mob.  That means that if the guild wants to advance, the vast majority of uber tank loot is going to fall onto a few people.  And those are going to be the people that are there raid after raid... that have the time (note I didn't say dedication... you can be dedicated, but still have real life committments that prevent you from having the time) and the skills to be the main tank.  <br>
<br>
Let's take an easy example.  Yedelma, pos dragon in WW.  Has no AoE attack, pure melee mob.  If your main tank can hold aggro, the rest of your melee class could fight him naked w/ just a haste item and weapons and be 99% as effective as they would be in full ToV armor.  Why?  Because if your strategy is tight, only one person should be taking any melee dmg at all.  <br>
<br>
Obviously, most of the time it's not quite that simple.  Mobs have aoe's so everyone else needs to have the best resists possible.  The main tank might lose aggro for a second or two, so naked is not a great way to fight.<br>
<br>
As a guild you can choose to try to outfit all of your tanks equally... but you aren't going to make any progress that way.  You're going to be stuck killing the same mobs over and over and over again until people get bored and start leaving.  And sure, loot would be equitable then... But if instead you gear up your main battle tanks and move on to better things, everyone will have better gear in the long run.  Those that don't have the time to be the main tanks won't be first in line for uber loot... but if they're in a guild that can do end game mobs, at least they'll be in line.  <br>
<br>
There's nothing wrong with deciding you'd rather go solo or stay in a more casual guild than to be warrior #10 or shaman #5 or cleric #999 in a large guild.  A lot of it depends on what you play for.  <br>
<br>
It's a tough balance.  It's something I struggle with as a guild leader.  I'm human and prone to error... prone to being influenced conciously or subconciously... But I continue to do the best I can and to want the best for everyone in my guild. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/upsyknight.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Psyknight</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Junior Member</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/10/01 11:25:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=345.topic&index=72>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.angelfire.com/tx2/keithklier/images/spectre3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: to all unguilded level 46plus here...</span><hr size=1> /wave Keleios! =) No, I'm not coming back, was just bored at work and had nothing better to do hehe. <br>
<br>
I dunno. I led a guild on Nameless from the time Gameless opened to the day Vazaelle opened. I think most of the negative attitude built around guilds have to do with the more successful guilds in terms of loot wise and the &quot;rat race&quot;<br>
<br>
My guild wasn't uber. We were a roleplaying social guild, at least originally. We had a very extensive application process and in the end, had a roleplaying event that included the entire guild for a quest type thing. Instead of us pushing levels to get to Hate, or something, we'd spend the entire night laughing in /gu while our applicant was trying to figure out the next part to the quest and run to guildmemberB to get the next step. It was great fun. Then as we grew and levels grew, the guild rotated towards raiding. I don't think some people understand how much the guild leader is actually led by the majority of the guild. If you don't do what the majority wants, people leave. I think this was the start of the downfall, the split between RP guild to Raid Guild. To keep your guild retention, you try to make them happy. <br>
<br>
I think for me personally, I don't think I've ever had a time where people didn't feel that they could speak their minds to me, regardless of loot. I think for one, because they trusted me as a person, and knew me as a friend. Each person, because we spent so much time and effort on their application process to get to know them on a personal level. I think on top of that, they weren't greedy about loot because it wasn't thought as an option in a roleplaying guild to get uber loot. Lastly, I think they understood the time and effort I put in to making the guild special for them and that I'd actually sit down and talk with each of them. Trust and communication is vital in any relationship, and must be constantly worked upon.  <br>
<br>
Well, as I learned what it was like to lead a raiding guild, I realized we needed class balance and levels. So, instead of roleplaying questing for joining, it went to recruitment for soandso levels for whichever classes. Clerics who were normally spending a few hours at the wall in Misty helping newbs and roleplaying with them, ended up spending 5 to 6 in Hate sweating not to screw a CHeal. Enchanters were begged to spend multiple hours and deaths to keep the raid rolling. New faces in the guild who had no intentions of roleplaying, but getting uber loot were in the guild and I think it created too much divergence too quickly. In the end, you had people one foot in, one foot out. <br>
<br>
If anybody asks if I was not fair on loot when it was distributed, I believe I was as fair as I could be, at least nobody, even after I was gone, bitched about how I did loot. Ask Moppin, who joined us on several consecutive Hate Raids, received a Indo BP even on top of my own guild's warriors. Though I kinda cringed, I felt I made the fair decision. <br>
<br>
Coming to Vazaelle, and shooting for the high end game, it just wasn't what I was looking for after I had aspirations about it. I just felt let down because I had high expectations. It's nobody's fault really but my own. I finally became disillusioned after I really delved in it. The guilds I was a part of, and even led in one case, were great people. I couldn't have asked for anything more than what they provided. I don't think it was the guild, I think it was my own expectations of how the high end game *could* be, and in reality, how different it was. <br>
<br>
The fact still remains, it doesn't have to be the way it is. But it takes a communal effort to change it to be a better situation. However, there will always be those who rely on the dissention and chaos to maintain power. A divide and conquer tactic. It works, but for me, it just makes me weary and sick of it. I just choose to bow out and find something funner to do. /shrug <p><b>Skeenk Da'Steenka<BR>
Iksar Disciple<BR>
<u><a href="http://www.promethianorder.com/">Promethian Order</a></u><BR>
Vazaelle Server</b><BR>
