<br>
 The guildleader position is a nightmare even with good personnel. And god forbid you make some bad recruiting decisions ! A leader has to stay on top of an incredibly immense and evolving game world, with changing mechanics and tactics.He has to properly equip an entire guild the best possible way he can.he has to schedule events while ensuring peoples RL schedules are considered and the proper classes are present.He has to schedule the order of those raids to best maximize progression of his peoples skill and equipment. All the while , keeping in mind different peoples varied levels of dedication to fellow members and the guild.Then he has to manage all the quirky personalities he has assembled and try  to keep them happy and feeling wanted. It would be  easier if the members stuck it out..cause eventually you will get to everyone. But alas, that does not happen. People leave for many reasons , and you are left starting from scratch with the new person that took his place.<br>
 Now take that stressed GL and put him in a Raid where he and his leaders are trying to manage  fifty things at once and ask him to know exactly what each person is wearing currently , compare it with a dropped item, sort out the greedy pricks that are JUST there for the loot and never help anyone else out for anything; and give it to the most deserving member or the member that will make the guild stronger as a whole. I say an impossible task to  do correctly all the time. And even when done correctly, it is  an objective decision. There will always be someone who feels somewhat slighted, even good players, with good hearts.( some are more vocal than others). This is natural, cause it is hard to sit thru a 5 hour raid and leave with nothing sometimes; even more so if the raid had some trouble along the way.<br>
  Now there are effective ways to manage a lot of these issues; Keadiaen(sp) touched on a few. I guess my main point , is that many people seem to expect  perfection from their guild. It is not gonna happen..EVER. Verant has made it necessary to operate  an efficient large scale guild in order to  attempt or complete all the challenges they have  set. Now while many gamers are more casual or are still exploring Norrath..other people have done all the old world and Kunark till they are bored to tears. The challenges they still want to attempt in this game require dedication, and organization. You can't see the results overnight though, and thats when people get frustrated and feeling used.  The Guilds that stick it out, are the ones that succeed. The people looking for instant gratification get fed up and leave. &quot;family guilds&quot; and the like are easier to manage, but those style guilds seldom end up on the rant board.<br>
  I don't know where I am headed with all this except to say,  more people need to balance their goals and expectations. This game is clearly not fun for many people, but they are too addicted to quit.Guilds should be a gathering of friends, hopefully skilled friends. But you cant put 50 random highly skilled players together and expect them to be succesful. You have to have friendships as a base or you will never survive the storms ahead.<br>
<br>
