<br>
But there is one very valid problem with that strategy. A problem that I imagine frustrates many guild leaders. If someone is a melee character in your guild, and is not one of the 3 'main tank warriors', is their desire to see themselves in a support role for the good of the guild stronger than their desire to be more of a core person in that guild? A guild can always survive by cycling in new 'not-the-main-tank-but-i-do-melee-sometimes' warriors, paladins, and sk's but then it's just a revolving door. How do you make this slant of item distribution hold their interest in being active enough to attend raids without having them harbor a desire to slide into one of those spots? How do you remove jealousy and contention?<br>
<br>
I imagine it's a pretty damn hard thing to get done in any group large enough to have this problem in the first place. I'd wager this spreads around also. You need clerics to heal. I'm sure the druids (who already made their strongest contribution to the raid by porting everyone there and casting a pair of buffs) have a valid reason to feel second rate. I don't think anyone has doubts on whether or not you need a paladin, or any type of hybrid to get something done.<br>
<br>
It just comes down to needing a warrior in high ac gear to main tank and so the items have to get dumped in that direction at the cost of the other members of the guild.<br>
<br>
In the long run, everyone will have those items (assuming the guild is making the right choice and keeping things together) but is it really worth making your main tank 5% more effective by disappointing 5% of your guild ? [random number, could be whatever]<br>
<br>
I think Procax has it right on with having a fair system in place. I also think if your main tank's capability to 'tank' a mob is so dependant on whether or not they upgrade each of their items by 2-3 ac, maybe the guild isn't ready for that encounter yet afterall.<br>
